properties.description: Hi.My name is Adrian and i'm a surveyor engineer in Romania. Well,what to tell, my life is like a search now, I'm trying to find my way. Unfortunately I dont't have many contacts in the U.S.A. and, due to lack of information, I don't know what my chances really are. I would be very greateful if by joining this land surveyors group i would find someone that would and could try to help me in this sense. I graduated the Faculty of Geodesy, the specilization Terrestrial Measurements and Cadastre, in one item- Surveying. This is also the field I've been working into in the last 3 years, since graduation. I would like to know if there is a possibility to have my education over there acknowledged and optionally to continue my studies there, for example to make a master degree...or whatever necessary to find o job in this domain. Another problem would be my visa. I already have a 10 year visa for U.S.A., but I assume that for studying or working I would be needing a student or working visa. So I should also be interested to know what the procedure for changing the visa status is. Well,my dear friend from us, thank you for reading this, I wish you all the best and say goodbye , with the hope that maybe you know someone who could provide you with this information or that maybe you find out something which could help me further. properties.description: I am a dedicated and proactive professional who has over 13 years experience leading major construction and civil engineering projects. I also possess strong business and commercial acumen having completed my Masters in Business Administration through to my Post Graduate Diploma in Project Management. I have an extensive array of skills and experience from the traditional services of land surveying, measured building surveying and precise engineering to the contemporary methods of GPS, laser scanning, GIS data collection and digital mapping. These skills have been applied across a wide ranging client base including development sites for retail, hospitality, commercial, residential, educational and medical purposes in addition to infrastructure projects including highways, railways and environmental commissions. I am inspired most when working on challenging and diverse projects and enjoy taking full ownership of the project from the initial design stages through to completion. I have a strong understanding of the drivers to change within individual projects whilst adopting a value driven approach to project management. My meticulous approach to project planning guarantees that medium to large scale projects are delivered on time, to the highest standard and in accordance with exacting specifications. properties.name: Bernie J. Marocco
properties.description: My early background in Surveying began in the 70's after completing a BA in English and then an Assoc. Degree in Land Surveying. My first land surveying work was very rewarding and interesting.It primarily involved extensive title search and retracing boundary evidence of large land tracks in the southern Adirondacks. These were still the days of theodolite and chain measurements for the most part. Then 2 years in the Peace Corps as an ag. extension agent in Sierra Leone doing primarily rice paddy development and Survey/Mapping support for paddy irrigation systems. After Peace Corps I went out to the west coast (CA)to work for the US Forest Service as a Transportation Planner, Logging Systems Specialist, wildland fire fighter, and eventually back into Cadastral Surveying with the USFS and BLM. My work as Party Chief of a Cadastral Survey crew involved retracing suspect and/or fraudulent 1880's GLO surveys in remote Northern CA mountains. After 35 years with the USFS, I'm now back East(PA) winding down my FS career and planning/building my next career as a private practice Licensed Professional Surveyor.Zoom in!

properties.description: I started Surveying with the Seabees in Vietnam in 1968. Have gone the gauntlet starting as a chainman, rodman, crewchief, surveyor in training to head surveyor with an engineering company. I have had my own business for about 20 years. I am very concerned about our profession going by the wayside and being replaced with GIS people who know very little about real property and title problems and solutions. I would like to be involved with the separation of the two professions but creation of a working environment that both share. I am fully aware of the significance of the technology that exist and its meaningful relationship with the Land Surveying aspect. I look forward to the GIS community developing a good working relationship with the Surveying Community that will enchance the capability of both Professions.Zoom in!

properties.name: DAVID C. GARCELON
properties.description: I now lecture and consult re: surveying, antique surveying instruments and surveying history...feel I can not only learn from others but also can help to mentor younger surveyors. I have been involved with such projects as the Central Artery/Third Harbor Tunnel in Boston, the Seabrook Nuclear Station in Seabrook, NH, the Vernon Nuclear Station in Vernon, VT., the 10,000 acre Mount Washington Hotel/Bretton Woods Ski Area in the White Mountains of New Hampshire. I have been the Chief Surveyor for several firms in the Boston area, as well as owned and operated my own Surveying/Engineerin business in Colebrook, NH for 12 years. I have the strong opinion that many surveyors have become so enarmored with modern technology that they forget that there were millions of boundaries established before they were born; those boundaries cannot be re-established by us. They can only be redefined. Defining a boundary to the nearest 1/100th of a foot and 1 second of arc can give us an unwarranted confidence in our work, especially if we have moved the original boundary. We must learn Boundary Law and the rules of evidence at the same time we learn how to use the tools and instruments..the tools and instruments constantly change but the laws and rules regarding the locations of boundaries has changed very little since the early 1600's. New tools and instruments allow us to mathematically redefine boundaries...their use does not give us permission to change the location of a long established boundary! We older surveyors need to learn the new technology and at the same time pass on our knowledge and experience re" boundary laws and the rules of evidence.Zoom in!

properties.description: AAM's surveying services include: surveying, mapping, aerial surveying, photogrammetry, geomatics, hydrographic surveying, and a wide range of other land technology based services which it carries out for the private, industrial and governmental sectors. properties.name: Mike Moe
properties.description: I grew up on a farm near a small Northwest North Dakota town called Tioga, where I graduated from high School in 1981. From there, I attended Dawson Community College in Glendive, MT, where I got my degree in land Surveying. Following school, I worked for the City of Williston, ND, Engineering Department, then my wife, Michelle and I moved to Racine, WI in 1987 where I worked for a consulting Engineering and Surveying Company called Nielsen Madsen and Barber. It was while in Racine where our oldest Daughter Brittany was born in 1990. In 1992, I accepted a job with Welch Land Surveying in Redgranite, WI. In 1994, our youngest daughter, Mariah, came along into our lives... Brittany finally got a baby sister! (all my boys are girls). In 1995, after Bob Welch lost the US Senate election to Senator Herb Kohl, I purchased the business from Bob. In 1997, I purchased Schindler Land Surveying in Wautoma, WI. Somehow around that same time I started into Commercial real Estate Development, and started 2 realestate development firms which are still operating today. In early 2007, I bought a Title Insurance Agency from First American Title Insurance Company, and I am spending alot of my time at the Title Company right now. The surveying end is still thriving. I am lucky to have such dedicated long-term employees. And of course, being a cheesehead, I love the Packers!!Zoom in!

properties.name: Mike
properties.description: Staff Sergeant in Vermont National Guard Mountain Recon Platoon. Married, father of three girls. I started surveying for a private company in 83, graduated from The Land Surveying Trianing Center in Tempe AZ in 85. Joined the DOT in Arizona in 85 on a photogrametric crew, moved To CT in 87 where I surveyed for 6 years in Meets and Bounds. Moved back to AZ and worked for a couple of engineering firms for six-years. Now my family and I are back on the east coast for good. Sick of the desert heat--love the snow! I spent 8 years in the Army, 3 years active duty in a RECON platoon working with land navigation and 5 years in the Arizona national guard in a military police unit. I spent January 1980 in Fairbanks Alaska. I climbed Mt. Rainier in Washington state and surveyed some of the Arizona desert. I surveyed a single planned subdivision, for an A.L.T.A. of 82,600 units, 24,600 acres or 39 sq. miles. Using Trimble GPS 5800 we finished it in 2 weeks with 2 crews.Zoom in!

properties.description: As a surveyor coming out from the italian high school, since I've got my diploma I've been more involved with site managing rather than plain surveying. Major projects in Munich's downtown and, right after that, the Allianz Arena, the new football stadium in Munich which hosted the opening game of the soccer's world championship 2006. After that I remained stuck to surveying and, sincerely, I don't have reasons to regret it. The sites remained big and demanding and the demand about my person just as well. properties.name: Robert R Sherman
properties.description: I have been extremely interested in the development and use of the State Plane Coordinate System throughout my career. I have also been involved in Airport Design for the last 25-years. As such we were responsible to tie in all of our work to the local State Plane Coordinate System in order to be able to provide accurate State Plane Coordinates for all Runway End points, NAV AIDS, etc. as well as Local Airport Coordinates (which are typically based on one of the major runway centerlines as due north with one runway end point assigned a specific local value. The FAA uses these Runway End Points in State Plane Coordinates in Order to utilize them to provide Navigational Guidance throughout our National Airspace. The amazing fact is that not that many Engineers and/or Surveyors that I have dealt with over the years, fully comprehend this system of coordinates.Zoom in!

properties.name: Steve L. Deveny
properties.description: Steve currently is employed as a Land Surveyor He has fifteen years of experience in the land survey industry which includes field and office time. He received his Land Survey Intern Certificate from the State of Nevada on the 15 of May, 2003 and his Professional Land Surveying License from the State of Nevada on the 10th of July, 2008. Steve started his caving career in 1995 with the Southern Nevada Grotto of the National Speleological Society and has served as Chairman of this Grotto for 14 years and Vice-Chairman for one year. Currently Steve is a Fellow and Member of the National Speleological Society, Chairman of the Southern Nevada Grotto, and adjunct instructor for the Collage of Southern Nevada. Volunteer projects that he has lead included the Nevada Association of Land Surveyors Mountain Top Survey Project; Lehman Caves Survey and Cave Inventory Projects for Great Basin National Park; Southern Nevada Visitation & Environmental Study and Nevada State Cave Data Base Project for the Southern Nevada Grotto; Gating and managing Wounded Knee Cave for the Bureau of Land Management. Volunteer projects that he has help with included Tonopah Community Gardens Project; Pinnacle Cave Cleanup and the Soda Straw Cave Re-closure Projects for Spring Mountains National Forest Service; Dante's Pit Cleanup Project for the State of Arizona; Desert Cave & Red Rock Cave Mapping Surveys for Desert Research Institute; Gypsum Cave Mapping & Record of Survey for Helen Morison, wife of Nevada State Congressman; Onyx Cave Mapping Survey for National Speleological Society Arizona Regional Association; Lehman Caves Trail Restoration Project for Great Basin National Park; Junior Speleological Society duties at three National Speleological Society Conventions. Steve believes that with the Southern Nevada Grotto's presence in Nevada, the Cave & Karst Systems in this state have a better chance of being protected, studied, and cared for. He offers his extensive knowledge to tZoom in!

properties.name: Tim Kent
properties.description: I started out working with my dad at age 8 tailing chain, Then as I got older and could see over the bushes I started cutting brush lines. Working with older people, I picked it up quick and at age 17 after grad. high school I found myself with a crew fulltime and have been out there ever since. Here in Louisiana every day brings something different . I worked for my dad to the day He passed in 62. I couldn't see wasting every thing he had built so my sister and I just kept going. Now at 51 the scars and bars have taken there toll But I just walk a little slower and have now stopped trying to jump the creeks instead I just wade the water and keep going while the crew keeps looking back to see if I've made it up the other side yet. All in all it's been a blast. My main question is what happened to the comrodary between surveyors, we use to be a tight group, now evryone seems scared to venture out of thier own little circle. Does any one else sense this?Zoom in!
